The SIR model - flattening the curve¶

Doukan E. Trkz

The SIR model is given by the following system of ODEs

$$ \dot S = - \frac{\beta S I}{N}, \quad \dot I = \frac{\beta S I}{N} - \gamma I, \quad \dot R = \gamma I, $$

where $S$ is the number of susceptible individuals, $I$ is the number of infectious individuals, $R$ is the number of recovered or removed individuals. $N$ is the total number of individuals, i.e. $N = S+I+R$. One can easily verify that $\dot N = 0$ by adding the three equations. Hence $N$ is constant. $\beta$ and $\gamma$ are parameters: $\beta$ is the average number of contacts per person per time, $\gamma$ is the reciprocal of the time an individual remains infectious. The basic reproduction ratio is given by $R_0 = \beta \;/ \;\gamma$. We are potentially interested in cases where the parameter $\beta$ is not constant in time.

# import libraries

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.integrate import odeint

Baseline case¶

The Python code cells below compute numerical solutions to this model by calling the SciPy ODE solver odeint.

Results are shown for specific parameter values: $\beta = 0.3$ and $\gamma = 0.1$, corresponding to $R_0 = 3$. The initial conditions are $S(0) = 10^6 - 5$, $I(0) = 5$, and $R(0) = 0$. So, we start with only 5 infectious individuals in a population of size $N=10^6$.

The first plot below shows the time series of the three variables. Time can be thought of a measured in days so 180 days is about 6 months. The model captures the basics of the disease progression where the number of infectious individuals initially grows (outbreak). Eventually the number of infections individuals reaches a peak and thereafter decreases.

In [2]:
# --- First define the RHS of ODE system --- #

def SIR(y, t):
    # returns RHS of the SIR model
    S, I, R = y

    beta = 0.3
    gamma = 0.1
    
    N = S + I + R
    Sdot = -beta * S * I / N
    Idot = beta * S * I / N - gamma * I
    Rdot = gamma * I
    
    return Sdot, Idot, Rdot

# --- Problem setup --- #

# Set initial conditions and put into array y0
S0 = 10.0**6 -5
I0 = 5
R0 = 0
y0 = np.array([S0, I0, R0])

# set up time grid for solution
tf = 180
Nsteps = 1800
t= np.linspace(0, tf, Nsteps+1)

# --- Call the ODE solver and extract solutions --- #
  
y_sol = odeint(SIR, y0, t)

# extract S, I, R from the solution array y
S = y_sol[:,0]
I = y_sol[:,1]
R = y_sol[:,2]

# --- Plot various interesting things --- #

# plot the time evolution of the S, I, R
plt.figure(figsize=(15,7.2))
plt.plot(t, S, label="S")
plt.plot(t, I, lw = 2, label="I")
plt.plot(t, R, label="R")



# labels etc
plt.xlabel("time", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("S,I,R", fontsize=14)
plt.title("SIR model", fontsize=16)
plt.legend(fontsize=14)
plt.show()

The second plot shows a phase portrait in the $(S,I)$ plane. A diamond shows the initial condition, and a circle shows the final state. The plots show a different view of the disease progression. Note that at the final time, there are some individuals who did not contract the disease ($S(t_f) > 0$).

print("I(t=tf) =", round(I[-1]))

The (rounded) maximum value of I is 300464, which occurs when (rounded) S = 332721.

Prior immunity¶

One can study the basic effect of immunity with the SIR model by starting from an initial condition in which a percentage of the population is in the $R$ class already. Think of these as individuals who have been removed from $S$ and put into $R$, either because they have prior natural immunity or because they have been vaccinated. Either way, they are immune and hence not susceptible at the start of the disease outbreak.

The Python code cells below compute numerical solutions to this model by calling the SciPy ODE solver odeint.

Results are shown for specific parameter values: $\beta = 0.3$ and $\gamma = 0.1$, corresponding to $R_0 = 3$. The initial conditions are $S(0) = 10^6 - 200005$, $I(0) = 5$, and $R(0) = 200000$. So, we start with only 5 infectious individuals in a population of size $N=10^6$, but we now also have $200000$ recovered individuals $(20 \%$ of $N$).

The first plot compares the time series of the three variables with prior immunity with the baseline case. Time can be thought of a measured in days so 180 days is about 6 months. Eventually the number of infections individuals reaches a peak and thereafter decreases in both cases. However, with prior immunity, $S$ decreases much more slowly and $R$ increases much more sharply compared to the baseline case. Furthermore, we have successfully flattened the curve, which was our main goal. We use the same colors as in the baseline case to make the graph easier to read.

# Set initial conditions and put into array y0

pr_I0 = 5
pr_R0 = 200000

# extract S, I, R from the solution array y

plt.plot(t, pr_R, label="prior immunity R", color = "green")
plt.plot(t, S, '--', label="S", color = "b")
plt.plot(t, I, '--', lw = 2, label="I", color = "red")
plt.plot(t, R, '--', label="R", color = "green")

# labels etc
plt.xlabel("time", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("S,I,R", fontsize=14)
plt.title("SIR model", fontsize=16)
plt.legend(fontsize=14)
plt.show()

The second plot compares the phase portraits in the $(S,I)$ plane of the number of infectious individuals with and without prior immunity. The plots show a different view of the disease progression. A diamond shows the initial condition, and a circle shows the final state in both cases. The green triangle and red triangle show the maximum number of infected individuals in both cases. Note that at the final time, the number of individuals who did not contract the disease is much higher with prior immunity.

Social distancing¶

One can model social distancing, or a mask mandate, by varying the parameter $\beta$ that controls the rate of infection. We will use the following simple approximation. When a mask mandate is in effect, the parameter $\beta$ will be reduced to 0.24, otherwise it will be 0.3, as in the baseline case. More specifically, we will consider $\beta$ to change between these two values according to:

$$ \beta = 0.3 \quad {\rm if} \quad t \le t_{m} \\ \beta = 0.24 \quad {\rm if} \quad t_{m} < t \le t_{m}+30 \\ \beta = 0.3 \quad {\rm if} \quad t_{m}+30 < t $$

$t_m$ corresponds to the time the mask mandate goes into effect. We consider a 30-day mandate period and so $t_m+30$ corresponds to the time the mask mandate is lifted.

Note, that with $\beta$ varying with time, the ODE is no longer autonomous and the reproduction rate is no longer constant.

As in the baseline case, the initial conditions are $S(0) = 10^6 - 5$, $I(0) = 5$, and $R(0) = 0$. So, we start with only 5 infectious individuals in a population of size $N=10^6$.

We first write a Python function to compute the right-hand-side of the SIR model with time-dependent $\beta$ given by the above expression. We will take $t_m = 43$, as this value for $t_m$ flattens the infected individuals curve significantly.

In [7]:
def soc_SIR(y, t):
    # returns RHS of the SIR model
    S, I, R = y
    
    # we implement the tm value discussed above to define beta in piecewise form
    
    tm = 43
    beta = 0
    if t <= tm or tm + 30 < t:
        beta = 0.3
    else:
        beta = 0.24
    
    gamma = 0.1
    
    N = S + I + R
    Sdot = -beta * S * I / N
    Idot = beta * S * I / N - gamma * I
    Rdot = gamma * I
    
    return Sdot, Idot, Rdot

The first plot compares the time series of the three variables with social distancing with the baseline case. Time can be thought of a measured in days so 180 days is about 6 months. Eventually the number of infections individuals reaches a peak and thereafter decreases in both cases. However, with social distancing, $S$ decreases more slowly and $R$ increases more sharply compared to the baseline case. Furthermore, we have successfully flattened the curve, which was our main goal. We use the same colors as in the baseline case to have an easier to read graph.

Concluding Remark: In an ideal scenario, it is seen from our analysis that a combination of prior immunity (perhaps in the form of vaccination) and social distancing (perhaps in the form of a maske mandate for a certain period of time) would flatten the curve most effectively, and hence, decrease the pressure over the healthcare systems.
